The '''(Great) Khurasan Road''' was the great [[trunk road]] connecting [[Baghdad]], the capital of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]], with the northeastern province of [[Khurasan]] and thence to [[Central Asia]] and [[Chinese Empire|China]].
== Course == [[File:Khurasan Road from Baghdad to al-Rayy.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map of the Khurasan Road from Baghdad to Rayy, according to Ibn Khordadbeh, with distances in ''[[farsakh]]s'']] It is possibly the best described of the roads of the Abbasid realm;{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|p=9}} not only is it described in detail by [[Ibn Rustah]], but most other medieval Muslim geographers such as [[Qudama ibn Ja'far]] and [[Ibn Khordadbeh]] refer to it and give distances along its various stretches in their works.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=12, 85}} The road began at the Khurasan Gate on the eastern side of the [[Round city of Baghdad|Round City]] of [[al-Mansur]], and exited the city at the second Khurasan Gate of East Baghdad.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|p=31}}
[[File:Khurasan Road from al-Rayy to Naysabur.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map of the road from Ray to Nishapur, with distances in ''farsakhs'']] The first settlement after Baghdad was Nahrawan or Jisr Nahrawan ("Bridge of Nahrawan"), named after the great [[Nahrawan Canal]] which passed through it. In the Abbasid period it was prosperous, but was abandoned and fell in ruin when the road moved north to [[Ba'quba]]. The surrounding district was known as ''Ṭarīq-i-Khurāsān'' after the Khurasan Road.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=59–61}} The next town was known in Arabic as Daskarah al-Malik ("Daskara of the [[malik|King]]"), and is identified with [[Sassanian]]-era [[Dastagird]]. Then followed [[Jalula]], near which a large Sasanian-era bridge crossed the [[Diyala River]], and [[Khanaqin|Khaniqin]], also the site of a major bridge, and [[Qasr Sjirin]], the "Castle of [[Shirin]]", named after the wife of the Sasanian shah [[Khosrow II]].{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=62–63}} At [[Hulwan]], the road left the [[Mesopotamia]]n plain and entered the [[Zagros Mountains]] and the province of [[Jibal]].{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=63, 191}} The road continued to Madharustan and finally exited the Hulwan pass at the town of [[Kerend-e Gharb|Kirind]] and the village of Khushan. Then followed Tazar or Qasr Yazid and al-Zubaydiya, where the road turned east towards [[Kirmanshah]] across the plain of Mayidasht or [[Mahidasht District|Mahidasht]]. On most of these localities, the Muslim geographers record the presence of remnants of Sasanian palaces.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=191–192}} From Kirmanshah the road continued to [[Hamadan]] and [[Sivah]], turned north to [[Rey, Iran|Rayy]], and from there passed east into the province of [[Qumis (region)|Qumis]].{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|p=228}} The road was the main lifeline of Qumis, and most of the province's towns were located along its course: [[Choara (Parthia)|Khuwar]], Qasr or Qariyat al-Milh (the "Salt Castle"), Ras al-Kalb ("Dog's Head", identifiable with [[Lasgird]]), [[Semnan, Iran|Samnan]], [[Damghan]], al-Haddadah ("the Forge") or [[Mihman-Dust]], and [[Bistam]]. Near Bistam, at the village of Badhash, the road entered Khurasan.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=364, 367–368}}
[[File:Transoxiana 8th century.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map of Khurasan and Transoxiana in the early Islamic period]] After entering Khurasan, the road divided in two: a northern branch, also called the "[[caravan (travellers)|caravan]] road", leading to [[Jajarm]], and thence via [[Azadvar]] to [[Nishapur]], and a shorter southern branch or "post road" along the edge of the [[Dasht-e Kavir]] desert, via [[Asadabad, Savadkuh|Asadabad]], Bahmanibad or [[Mazinan]], and [[Sabzivar]], again to Nishapur.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|p=430}} Shortly after Nishapur, at Qasr al-Rih ("Castle of the Wind"), the road divided again into two branches leading southwest and northeast. The southwestern branch led to [[Herat]], from where it branched out further, with roads leading east to [[Ghur]], or via [[Asfuzar]] and [[Farah, Afghanistan|Farah]] south to [[Zaranj]] in [[Sijistan]].{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=430–431}} The northeastern branch of the main road led from Qasr al-Rih via [[Mashhad]], [[Tus, Iran|Tus]], [[Mazdavand|Mazdaran]], and [[Sarakhs]] to [[Merv|Marw the Great]] and [[Marw al-Rudh]]. From Marw the Great the road continued to the crossing of the [[Oxus River]] at [[Türkmenabat|Amul]] and on to [[Bukhara]] and [[Samarkand]]. From Marw al-Rudh a branch led south to Herat, while another went northeast to [[Balkh]] and, likewise crossing the Oxus, to [[Tirmidh]], whence it branched out to various roads into the districts of [[Saghaniyan]] and [[Khuttal]], while another branch led west to Bukhara and Samarkand.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=430–431, 472}} From Amul, another branch also led along the southern bank of the Oxus to [[Khwarizm]] and the [[Aral Sea]].{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|p=472}} From Samarkand, the road crossed the [[Zeravshan River|Sughd River]] and led to the town of [[Zaamin, Uzbekistan|Zamin]] in [[Usrushana]], east of the local capital, [[Bunjikath]]. There the road divided again, with one branch leading north to [[Shash]] and the lower course of the [[Jaxartes]], and the other east to the upper course of the Jaxartes, the [[Ferghana Valley]] and China.{{sfn|Le Strange|1905|pp=475, 488}}
